# Design Decisions — 2026-04-14
## Session: Dairy — first insertion batch + two naming conventions resolved

---

### Decision 8: Source naming follows `{family} {specific}` format

Naming convention: the family or genus name comes first, the specific qualifier second.
`milk cow` not `cow milk`. `milk buffalo` not `buffalo milk`.

**Why:** A taxonomy-first convention. All milk sources group together alphabetically and
in any sorted output. All wheat sources group together. The structure of the name mirrors
the structure of the graph — hierarchy flows left to right: the broader thing first,
the specific thing second. This is consistent with how scientific nomenclature works
(Bos taurus, not taurus Bos) and with how lookups will behave: a query for all members
of the milk family returns `milk cow`, `milk buffalo`, `milk camel` without needing
any join on source-type.

This applies to ALL sources going forward. Sources already in the DB before this session
(`cow milk`, `buffalo milk`, `camel milk`) need renaming to match.

**Scope:** source-name attribute values only. form-id values are not affected — forms
are not taxonomically qualified the same way.

---

### Decision 9: Multi-word processing-method values use hyphens, not spaces

`spray-drying` not `spray drying`. Same rule applies to any multi-word processing-method
value going forward.

**Why:** Consistency and downstream safety. Hyphenated values are unambiguous as single
tokens in queries, exports, and any pipeline that splits on whitespace. A space inside
an attribute value is legal in TypeDB but creates fragility everywhere else — CSV columns,
JSON serialisation, CLI tools, and future lookup-layer logic all handle hyphens more
cleanly than embedded spaces. The ref list (`ref/processing-method_list.csv`) used spaces
in the `value` column — that file should be updated to reflect the hyphenated standard.

Existing processing-method values in the DB: `churning`, `clarification`, `fermentation`,
`skimming`, `whole-milling`, `refined-milling`, `coarse-milling`, `malting`, `flaking`
— none of these were multi-word, so no back-migration needed. `spray-drying` is the
first multi-word value inserted; it sets the precedent.

---

### Decision 10: Ghee is form-of(source) directly — not form-of(butter)

Ghee could be modelled as `butter → [clarification] → ghee`, which is technically
accurate as a production chain. This was considered and rejected.

**Why:** The same reasoning that prevents whole wheat flour and refined wheat flour from
being modelled as one being form-of the other. Both butter and ghee are independently
declarable forms. When a brand declares "ghee", the source they select on the IFID input
form is `milk cow` or `milk buffalo` — not `butter`. The intermediate step (churning
cream to get butter) is part of the production process but not a declared ingredient
in that product.

Modelling ghee as form-of(butter) would:
1. Make "all forms of cow milk" a two-hop query (you'd have to traverse through butter)
2. Imply butter is always a necessary declared intermediate — it isn't (direct ghee
   production from cream without separate butter production is common)
3. Mix processual steps with declared ingredient relationships, which is exactly what
   `processing-method` on `form-of` is designed to avoid

The correct model: ghee is `form-of(milk cow, [churning, clarification])`. Two
processing-method attributes on the relation. The multi-step production chain is
readable from the attribute set; no chain of nodes is needed.

---

### Decision 11: Taxonomy root (`milk`) never appears as form-of origin

All form-of relations for dairy forms connect to `milk cow` and `milk buffalo` directly —
not to `milk` (the taxonomy root, `is-declarable: false`).

**Why:** A form-of relation encodes what a brand actually declares: "this product
contains [form] derived from [source]". `milk` cannot be declared — the IFID input
form requires source specificity. Anchoring form-of to `milk` would create relations
that have no valid instantiation in the real world. If a brand could declare "milk",
IFID's core value proposition (enforcing source specificity at input) would be
undermined structurally in the graph itself.

The `milk` node remains useful: it is the traversal target for "all dairy sources"
queries via `variety-of`. `milk cow variety-of milk`, `milk buffalo variety-of milk`.
That query is clean and correct. But `milk` sits at the top of the taxonomy; it does
not sit at the base of any form-of edge.

This principle generalises: no `is-declarable: false` source should ever appear as
`form-of:origin`. The two attributes (`is-declarable` and the form-of role) enforce
the same constraint from different angles.

---

### Decision 12: Yogurt and curd are separate form-id nodes

Both are fermented milk, both semi-solid, both use `fermentation` as processing-method.
They are still two form-ids.

**Why:** FSSAI has distinct product standards for each. Yogurt requires specific starter
cultures (Streptococcus thermophilus + Lactobacillus bulgaricus); dahi/curd uses
traditional starter without that constraint. They appear as separate declared items on
labels — a product labelled "dahi" is not interchangeable with one labelled "yogurt"
from a regulatory standpoint. The distinction is declaration-level, which is exactly
the level IFID operates at.

The fact that they share the same processing-method value and matter-state is not a
reason to collapse them. Two paths to the same node would mean any query for "products
containing curd" would also return "products containing yogurt". That is wrong.
Form-id is the declared identity. Declared identity differs. Two nodes.

---

### Decision 13: Camel milk excluded from this insertion batch

`milk camel` is in the DB as a source. The 6 forms inserted this session (butter, ghee,
cream, curd, yogurt, milk-powder) were connected to `milk cow` and `milk buffalo` only.

**Why:** Camel milk is commercially marginal in the Indian market relative to cow and
buffalo milk. For the forms in this batch, camel milk-derived versions are not common
declared ingredients in Indian packaged food. Including form-of relations for camel milk
before there is evidence of those forms appearing on Indian labels would be adding
structure without a corresponding real-world signal.

This is not a principled exclusion — camel milk CAN produce all these forms. It is a
priority decision. When camel milk dairy products appear in the IFID label corpus, the
form-of relations can be added then. The node exists; the edges can be added at any time.

---

### What was inserted this session

**ingredient-form nodes (6 new):**
- `butter` (fat fraction)
- `ghee` (fat fraction)
- `cream` (emulsion)
- `curd` (semi-solid)
- `yogurt` (semi-solid)
- `milk-powder` (powder)

**form-of relations (12 new):**
- Each of the 6 forms × 2 sources (milk cow, milk buffalo)
- Processing methods per form: butter→churning, ghee→churning+clarification,
  cream→skimming, curd→fermentation, yogurt→fermentation, milk-powder→spray-drying

**Schema change (done before this session by Lalitha):**
- `variety-of` extended to `ingredient-form → ingredient-form`
- Unblocks cheese subtype insertion

---

### Open questions carried forward

1. Is "whey" declared bare on Indian labels? (Determines whether whey gets a form-id
   node, or whether WPC/WPI connect directly to source.)

2. Does form-level variety-of appear outside dairy? (Must confirm before treating it as
   a general mechanism rather than a dairy-specific pattern.)

3. `milk` source-names need back-migration to `{family} {specific}` format
   (`milk cow`, `milk buffalo`, `milk camel`). Schema is unchanged; only attribute
   values need updating.
